For a number of years, Wangelis Maimarakis was part of the centre-right governments that led the country to the financial crisis, according to the left.
Now he, as the interim leader of the New Democracy party, is challenging Cyprus.
A few days before the election, he met with journalist Euronews.
Euronews: Mr. Maimarakis, welcome to Euronews!
Vangelis Maimarakis: Thank you for the invitation.
Euronews: Nine months ago, your party suffered a crushing defeat by subjugating the Syrian coalition, but now, according to polls, the “New Democracy” has been compared to it in popularity.
What has changed during this time?
Vangelis Maimarakis: Greece has changed, and so have we.
Mr. Tsipras lied a lot in January last year.
Nine months ago, Greece had a budget surplus and prospects for economic growth.
The country now has a budget deficit and a high level of unemployment.
The investors left because Mr. Tsipras threw them away.
Over the past nine months, the Greeks have had the opportunity to assess the situation in which the country was in January, and the false promises of Mr. Tsipras.
And now they can easily compare what was promised with what actually happened.
Daily life has become noticeably worse compared to January, when the situation improved, and this affected most Greek citizens.
Euronews: But you say that in the event of an election victory, you will seek alliances with other parties, including Syria.
Vangelis Maimarakis: The point is that, as we have understood in recent years, Greece cannot move forward without understanding and cooperation.
And it is not by chance that in all the other countries where rescue programmes have been or are still in operation, political forces and all the ruling parties have come together to implement a programme by which they have reached agreement without giving up their political or ideological autonomy.
That is why I firmly believe that at this stage only the cooperation of political forces and institutions will allow the country to move forward.
Euronews: Your party has voted in favour of an agreement between Mr. Tsipras and the country’s creditors.
If you become the new prime minister on Monday, will you fulfill this agreement, or will you try to change it at least in part?
Wangelis Maimarakis: We actually voted for Greece’s movement on the European path, because we are well aware of the devastating consequences the country’s exit from the EU would have.
Now Europe is helping us by providing subsidies to our farmers for their products, we have solidarity funds, the Juncker package and assistance in the banking sector.
All of this would have been lost without a treaty with Europe.
But the current austerity measures were the result of Mr Tsipras’ negotiations.
I know that Europe does not want to destroy us.
Europe wants to help us.
Thus, if Europe sees that the new Greek government in the first year wants to establish order, acts rationally and makes it clear that the country has a strong political will to implement the rescue program, then I am sure that all the commitments made by the government, which can not be fulfilled, will be fulfilled from the beginning.
It would be wrong to believe that in the first year of the new agreement, we will be able to return to negotiations with our creditors, as they expect the full implementation of the agreement.
If we want to restore their trust, we must continue the privatisation, reforms and structural changes that have been agreed, continuing to benefit from the benefits of EU funding and the great investment opportunities that we must open up for better understanding and cooperation with Europe.
Unfortunately, during the negotiations, the Government of Cyprus has not presented any serious arguments on many key political issues, which we have found out by discussing these issues with our European colleagues.
I can give you an example of farmers’ income.
We explained to our European partners that this is not a fixed monthly income, and therefore it cannot be fully taxed in advance.
We were told that the Cypriot ministers had never spoken about it.
That is, the Greek ministers were unprepared and ill-informed, and therefore failed to negotiate and conclude a failed agreement.
Euronews: If you win the election, you will soon be at the same table with Mr. Juncker, Mr. Hollande, Mrs. Merkel and other European leaders.
Will what you tell them differ from what your predecessor, Antonis Samaras, told them?
Wangelis Maimarakis: First of all, I will explain to them that by the end of 2014, we were trying to best implement the 2012 agreement, bypassing the sharp corners in it.
We are moving forward with reform.
Of course, we did not have the necessary determination and speed, but we acted under extreme circumstances.
The market fell, and there were no potential buyers willing to pay the price set by the Greek government.
At the time, I was the Speaker of Parliament, and I was able to agree on the views of three parliamentary groups that made up the government majority at the time.
And despite their serious ideological differences over key bills, we had a working parliament, in the presence of populists and extremists, as well as mass demonstrations going on outside.
And we managed to bring the country into a normal situation that would continue to improve if the process had not been interrupted by the early general elections that resulted from the December presidential elections.
Euronews: In recent weeks, there has been a massive influx of refugees across Greece.
What do you think about this situation and the reaction of the European countries in which these people aspire?
Vangelis Maimarakis: The refugee crisis is a slow-moving bomb that we have to deal with after winning the election.
And the reason is that the Syrian government did not act in this situation as follows.
In such matters, action should be taken in advance, because if the problem reaches you, only emergency measures remain.
And we are in this situation now.
Even the interim government that replaced Syria did more in just seven days than Mr. Tsipras did in seven months.
I am confident that these actions of the interim government, which is given valuable assistance by the President of the Republic, who is calling for the EU summit, will allow us to find a solution.
We need to see how many refugees will be able to leave the country, and notice that refugees are not illegal immigrants.
They are the victims of the war in Syria, the victims of some extraordinary events that happened to them.
This issue has a deeply humanitarian aspect, and we will stick to the positions that European politicians must take in this new situation.
The relevant decision should be taken at the EU summit, and the United Nations should be involved.
We also need better coordination of action, more effective border control, and refugee reception centres.
We must also make effective use of the economic assistance we receive from the EU in order to be able to cope with this urgent problem.
Euronius: Mr. Maimarakis, thank you for the interview.
Vangelis Maimarakis: Thank you.
