"Sonogenetics" allows you to control brain cells using sound waves
The video shows how nematodes change the direction of movement at a time when they are exposed to sound impulses.
Scientists have removed worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can be controlled using pulses of sound waves.
Tiny nematodes change the direction of motion at a time when they are affected by sound impulses that are too high for the human ear to hear them.
Impulses are impacted by activation of neurons that are genetically modified to use membrane channels that respond to ultrasound waves.
Next Next post: Researchers manage brain activity with the help of light
Scientists have said that the worms demonstrate the possibilities of a new method called "sonagenetics", the essence of which is the use of ultrasound to stimulate certain cells of the brain, heart and muscle, while the source of ultrasound is located outside the body.
Shrikant Chalasani, a research fellow at the Salco Institute in La Hoya, California, told the Guardian that this technique could one day replace deep brain stimulation — an invasive procedure that uses electric pulses and pulses in the human brain.
The nematode worms usually do not respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that they began to respond when they were placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
He found that the bubbles amplify the ultrasonic waves, which then penetrate into the body of the worms.
Intensified ultrasound waves affect structures called TRP-4 ion channels, which are found in the membranes of some intestinal cells.
Ultrasound waves cause these ion channels to open and excite the cells that are associated with them, according to a report in Nature Communications.
To create a nematode that can be controlled by ultrasound, Chalasani made genetic modifications to the worms, so that their motor neurons used TRP-4 ion channels.
During the application of ultrasound to affect modified organisms, sound waves were amplified by microscopic bubbles and introduced into the organisms of worms, activating modified motor neurons.
This method is similar to that used in "optogenetics" - a new direction that allows scientists to turn on and off neurons using light pulses.
Chalasani argues that compared to this method, sonogenetics may have some advantages.
Unlike light, which is delivered to the right part of the brain by fiber optics, low-frequency ultrasound waves pass unhindered through the tissues of the body, so for their delivery there is no need to pass inside the spinal cord.
“We believe that for the treatment of some neurological diseases in clinical conditions, the use of gene therapy and therapeutic viruses will be able to make human neurons sensitive to the ultrasound signal for a while,” Chalasani said.
He added that in addition, the method can be applied to muscle and insulin-producing cells.
