Kiev has officially formalized the refusal of Ukraine to cooperate with Russia on the completion of Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant.
The Supreme Council on Wednesday, with the second attempt, still voted for the termination of the agreement with Moscow.
Agreements on the completion of the third and fourth blocks were signed in 2010-2012, but the project has not been implemented.
On Wednesday, the Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine passed a law repealing the agreement concluded in 2010-2012 with the Russian Federation on the construction of the third and fourth block on Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant.
The bill passed by the country’s government has only been passed since the second vote, first supported by 210 deputies with a minimum of 226, but then 234 members of parliament voted in favour of the draft.
The Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant, which was laid under the Soviet Union, was supposed to have four 1 GW power units with VVER type reactors, but only two were built.
Negotiations with Moscow on completion led to the conclusion of an intergovernmental agreement by 2010 and in 2011-2012 the Council adopted the relevant laws.
Since there were no funds in the budget of Ukraine, it was assumed that the blocks would have to be built on a loan from the Russian side, but the funds were never allocated.
After the coup in Kiev in February 2014 and the subsequent cooling in relations between the two countries Kiev began to twist relations with Moscow in the nuclear industry, announcing the refusal to cooperate on Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant and on the project of construction of a nuclear fuel plant in Ukraine.
The only sphere where the relations have survived remained the purchases in the Russian Federation of fuel for the current Ukrainian nuclear power plants (provided about half of the electricity production in the country), as so far the Ukrainian NAEC "Energoatom" will replace Russian supplies.
