The decline in the forecast is observed despite an average rate hike of 4.9 percent, which will come into effect on January 4, and an increase in fees for ground transportation of heavy or bulk cargo, which begins in November.
The company said it still plans to increase revenue compared to last year, thanks to a reduction in costs, an increase in gross income and an increase in online commerce.
Chairman and CEO Fred Smith said the company "worked steadily given the weak, compared to the forecast, economic conditions, especially in manufacturing and world trade."
Plans to hire a workforce at the holidays were announced the day after a competitor’s statement, UPS, that they plan to hire an additional 95,000 employees, about the same as they took on work last year.
For the quarter that ended August 31, FedEx earned $692 million, up 6 percent from a year earlier.
