Revenue increased by 5%, to $12.3 billion.
Six analysts polled by Zacks estimated $12.23 billion.
FedEx has suffered in recent years from a decline in the sector of urgent international transportation, which has led to a lack of gross income growth in its express transportation division.
However, the online shopping boom has dramatically improved the results in the FedEx Ground.
In the last quarter, revenues from ground transportation increased by 29%, but operating revenues remained unchanged overall due to increased costs for large shipments and self-insurance.
The express-transport division received higher income due to higher base rates, while in the freight sector, income fell due to increased labor costs.
At pre-trades about an hour before the opening of the stock exchange FedEx fell by $3.85 or 2.5 percent – to $150.15.
They closed Tuesday, falling 11 per cent year-on-year and 17 per cent below the June 11 record.
At the most anticipated meeting in a few years, the leaders of the Federal Reserve System will spend two days this week behind a 27-foot table of the Honduran red tree, deciding whether it is time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in almost ten years.
At one end of the richly decorated room for meetings of two floors above them will hang a walled image of the United States.
This map is a reminder that Federal Reserve Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should place the economic interests of the country above all others.
The central bank received a double mandate from Congress: to maximize employment in the United States and to keep stable prices here.
But since the Great Recession, the leaders of the Federal System have acknowledged that there is a third, unwritten mandate: financial stability.
And this third order could prove to be an unknown factor in an almost-anticipated decision to announce on Thursday whether the U.S. economy is ready to break away from the unprecedented stimulus provided by an almost zero short-term interest rate since the end of 2008.
Even though most of the data shows a confident growth of the economy, recent shocks in the global financial markets can hold the already cautious leaders of the federal system from adding volatility by raising the base rate on federal funds – even by just a quarter.
“Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the first and most important subject of consideration,” said Lindsey M. Peegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“However, I think that if they were looking for a reason not to raise rates, the increased uncertainty around the world market is enough to give them an excuse to wait further,” she said.
There is no consensus on what to do in the Federal Reserve system, which in itself provokes fluctuations in the financial market.
Roughly half of economists, recently polled by Bloomberg, predicted interest rate growth this week.
Financial markets, however, expect the Federal system to refrain from doing so, while the key indicator shows only about a 30 percent probability of a rapid rise.
This could lead to a fall in the stock market if the federal system raises the rate, provided that those who make decisions do not soften the blow by promising that the next increase will be soon.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones index rose by 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The take-off was spurred by expectations that those defining the federal system’s strategy will leave the stake this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research.
"It will be a surprise if the Federal system raises rates at this point in time," he said.
If the Federal Reserve’s leadership does so, “they will have to go a long way in approving their strategy to keep financial markets in their hands so they don’t panic.”
Other experts objected that raising the rate could calm financial markets, as this would ease uncertainty about how the Federal system would operate.
Just a month ago, the federal system seems to have tended to raise the rate by 0.25% this month, taking the first small step in a slow tightening of financial conditions, which could confirm the resilience of the US recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expects the rate to rise this year, despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although the emergence of new jobs in August has slowed, the growth of the labor market has been stable this year.
Unemployment fell to 5.1% last month, which is the lowest rate in more than seven years, and almost at the level that the Federal system considers full employment.
The increase in wages shows signs of acceleration.
And while inflation continues to be below the central bank’s target of 2% per year, the Federal system’s management said the key cause was the temporary effect of a sharp drop in oil prices.
“The economy will also be able to cope with higher rates, and it needs them, given the shrinking labor market,” said Ian Schefferdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world began to shake at the end of last month, after China devalued its currency.
The Dow-Jones average index for industrial company stocks fell by as much as 16% in a record high in May, as investors feared that a slowdown in China’s economy could slow global growth.
The market partially recovered its positions this month, and the Dow Jones index is now about 10 percent below its May high.
For the leadership of the Federal Reserve, the market upsets further complicates the difficult calculations of the rate increase period.
“In the absence of information on what happened in the financial markets and news about the weakness of the Chinese economy in the past few weeks, they would start to spin the hooks at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, senior researcher at UCLA’s Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former employee of the Federal System Reserve.
Now, according to his predictions, they will wait at least a month to get more control over the consequences.
"There is a great deal of uncertainty as to what the consequences may be for the U.S. economy, and they have almost no reliable data after recent events in China," Oliner said.
The health of the world economy is not one of the main concerns of the Federal system, and it should not be taken into account technically when making these decisions.
But in essence, the Federal Reserve has become the world’s financial power.
The influence of the Central Bank in recent years has been enormous.
Just a hint from then-president Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Federal Reserve system could “absorb” its monetary expansion caused shocks to markets around the world.
In a world where markets and economic systems are increasingly intertwined, it could be expected that the leaders of the Federal Reserve System will not only monitor developments everywhere, but also consult with representatives of other central banks and experts to better understand the world economy.
Their decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Carabell, head of Envestnet Inc., a company that deals with global state-of-the-art strategies.
Jeffrey Lacer, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Virginia, noted this month that “in the history of the Federal Reserve, there have been cases of overreaction to financial market movements that seem unrelated to economic principles.”
Lacer, a member with the right to vote of the influential Federal Open Market Committee, who insisted on raising the rate, cited 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The financial crisis in Asia has led the federal system to lower its base rate by 0.75% in three sessions, “despite the limited identifiable consequences for growth in the U.S.,” Laker said.
A year later, the leaders of the federal system cancelled these reductions.
The Federal Reserve should put stability first only in times of major crises, such as the 2008 market collapse,” said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England interest rate committee.
The last panic and closeness did not approach this level, he said.
“Of course, you wouldn’t want to be in a situation where you’re afraid of rising rates because markets are experiencing shock,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute of the World Economy.
The Federal Reserve Act in the past has a dual mandate and does not mention financial stability, and as long as that does not change, I do not think that they should precede events.
