Diabetics with low obesity may be able to help weight loss surgery
The beneficial effect after obesity surgery in people with low obesity who suffer from type 2 diabetes can last at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is still too early to claim that low-fat diabetics live longer after obesity surgery than those who receive non-surgical treatment.
“Death statistics don’t show up immediately,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert on obesity surgery who wrote about the new study in the column of editor JAMA Surgery.
Obesity surgery, or bariatric surgery, uses various methods to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the ability of organisms to absorb food.
For several years, bariatric surgery has proven to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but major studies have been conducted among people with morbid obesity who have a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
IMT, a measure of weight relative to growth, is considered normal at a value from 18.5 to 24.9.
IMT 25 or higher indicates that a person has excess weight, and people with IMT over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your IMT here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers from Taiwan’s Min-Sheng General Hospital used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery – gastric shunt and hand gastrectomy, with medical treatment for type 2 diabetes in people with low obesity.
The average IMT value among those who underwent surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of their participation in the study.
At the same time, IMT in those who received non-surgical treatment from diabetes remains at approximately level 29.
Among those who underwent the surgery, 36% were completely cured of diabetes, and in part - 28%.
In the group receiving drug treatment, for comparison, complete treatment from diabetes was observed only in 1%, and partial - only in about 2%.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “in general were better in the surgical group,” the authors say.
The researchers also controlled hemoglobin levels of A1s in the blood, which reflect blood sugar levels in dynamics.
Hemoglobin A1c is better to keep below 7%, the researchers write.
After surgery, the average level of hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
In the therapeutic group, however, it remained stable, at about 8%.
But the best rates of glycemic control reflected by good levels of hemoglobin A1c did not reduce the death rate in five years, according to research lead Dr. Chi-Cheng Su and colleagues.
The research group also compared the average results of two types of surgical treatment.
In the fifth year, compared with the arm gastrectomy group, the shunt group lost more weight (18.7 kg versus 14.2 kg), achieved a greater reduction in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and hemoglobin A1s (3.1 % versus 2.1%), and was also closer to full-fat divisibility (16.1% versus 2.1%).
Although the new study does not demonstrate the benefits of the surgical method in terms of lifespan after five years, there is evidence from the study of people with excess body weight in Sweden that surgical treatment really leads to an increase in lifespan, according to Ulysses.
According to a Swedish study for people with obesity who chose bariatric intervention, the probability of dying for 15 years was about 29% lower compared to a group that used more traditional methods.
Despite the fact that the new study did not show an increase in lifespan, Blackstone noted that this encourages people with IMT below 35 interested in such a procedure.
“The report is very important here because it claims that such surgical intervention is safe in a group with low BMI, where there is no increased risk of death or kidney disease,” she said.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously as soon as a patient’s BMI falls in the range of 27 to 30.
"I think we're waiting too long to get people to take this seriously," she said.
It seems to me that once they accumulate the genetic changes that trigger obesity and diabetes in their bodies, it is very difficult to turn it back.
