Hewlett-Packard to cut up to 30,000 jobs
Hewlett-Packard plans to cut between 25,000 and 30,000 jobs as part of its Restructuring and Cost Reduction programme.
In the same year, Hewlett-Packard will be split into two companies registered on the company's stock exchange, separating the production of computers and printers from the more rapidly developing sectors of hardware and service operations.
Calculations as a result of the projected job cuts will amount to about $2.7 billion, starting in the fourth quarter, Hewlett-Packard said in a statement.
“This restructuring will provide a more competitive, sustainable cost structure for the new Hewlett Packard Enterprise,” said Meg Whitman, chairman and CEO of Hewlett Packard, which will lead the organization after the split.
“The Hewlett Packard Enterprise will be smaller and more focused than the Hewlett-Packard currently, and the business direction portfolio will be wider and deeper, which will help move the company to a new business style,” Whitman said.
As a separate company, we are in a better position than before to respond to the growing demands of our customers around the world.
Hewlett Packard Enterprise will have an annual revenue of more than US$50 billion and “will focus on providing previously unattainable integrated technology solutions” to companies, the company said in a statement.
This is how the company, formed in the 1930s by graduates of Stanford University, Bill Hullett and Dave Pacard, split up to produce electrical equipment; their garage in Palo Alto was called "the birthplace of Silicon Valley".
Hewlett Packard is in the process of large-scale reorganization with the aim of transitioning from traditional personal computers to mobile devices.
This move by HP, the world’s second-largest personal computer manufacturer and one of the largest tech companies in the U.S., is the latest in the industry, based on the belief that highly specialized companies are working better.
