News Economy <0xE2><0x80><0x95> Nobel Laureate: Globalization
To print out the processes of globalization had to contribute to the reduction of inequality in the world.
In fact, the situation looks different, the difference in the income of the population in developing economies, on the contrary, is growing.
Eric Maskin.
To correct this, it is necessary to increase the level of education of low-skilled workers, according to Eric Maskin, the chief scientific officer of the International Laboratory for Analysis and Choice of Decisions of the University of Applied Sciences, winner of the 2007 Nobel Prize in Economics.
In the last twenty years, the world has experienced unprecedented growth in global markets.
The trade borders between the two countries have become increasingly open.
Proponents of globalization have predicted great benefits for the developing economies.
“And these predictions have largely come true,” Maskin emphasizes.
For example, China and India have seen a significant increase in GDP per capita.
However, not everything is so cheerful.
Globalization was expected to reduce the gap between “poor” and “poor” countries, which manifests itself in large income inequality, or more precisely, wages.
But in fact, this inequality has only increased, notes Eric Maskin in his article “Why global markets have not reduced inequality in developing economies”, published in The World Bank Economic Review, which was translated and quoted by NIE WSE.
Together with the economist, Michael Kremer, professor at Harvard University, Eric Maskin developed an alternative theory that demonstrates why the income gap in poor countries is increasing as globalisation grows, according to the WSE.
There are specific processes taking place in the new global market.
To demonstrate them, Maskin allocates four levels of qualification of specialists - A and B for rich countries, C and D - for the poor.
After globalization, specialists D from poor countries lack the level of qualification to cooperate with specialists A and B from rich countries.
And if C-level workers from poor countries are growing wages through cooperation with B-level workers from the rich, then D-level workers are not feeling or their wages are falling at all.
The final effect is that the internationalization of production will contribute to an increase in the pay gap between the two categories of specialists in poor countries and, accordingly, to an increase in inequality.
Kremer and E. Maskin proposed an amazingly beautiful model, an alternative to Ricardian theory of comparative advantages.
It explains why globalization has led to income inequality, says Fuad Aleskerov, an ordinary professor who leads the International Laboratory of Analysis and Choice of Decisions, head of the Department of Mathematics of the University of Athens.
And like any powerful theory, I'm sure it will lead to a surge of empirical work in this area.
The solution of the problem, according to Eric Maskin, is to increase the level of education of low-skilled workers.
However, according to the scientist, the workers themselves do not have the means to do so, and it is not profitable for companies to pay for their training.
In such a situation, governments, international agencies, NGOs and private funds can play a significant role, according to Maskin.
The scientist notes that the developed theory does not in any case call for a halt to the process of globalization, which has brought and bears fruit in the form of GDP growth of countries.
