The U.S. Embassy regrets the closure of the American Center in Moscow.
The U.S. Embassy in Russia expressed regret over the closure of the Library of Foreign Literature of the U.S. Center.
The center has been working in Moscow for over 22 years.
The U.S. Embassy in Moscow deeply regrets the unilateral decision of the Russian government to close the American Center of the U.S. Embassy at the All-Russian State Library named after M.I.Rudomino in Moscow.
“The unilateral steps taken by the Russian Federation recently put into question the commitment of the Russian government to relations between the Russian and American peoples, which did not break even during the Cold War and other difficult moments of the long history of relations of our countries,” the statement said.
The American Center has created deep and strong connections between the people and culture of Russia and the United States.
It was the center of American culture, history and literature in the Russian capital, and served as a meeting place for numerous American prominent figures, including cosmonauts, artists, athletes, scientists, politicians and writers.
“Last year alone, the American Center held more than 400 cultural and educational events and welcomed more than 50,000 Russian visitors,” the diplomat said.
Tefft recalled that about a year ago it was decided to close another joint Russian-American project - the educational exchange program FLEX (Future Leaders Exchange Program).
The Green Tribunal was soon to be put to trial.
Typical situation: four officials stand at the table of Judge Svatanter Kumar, listening to his claims to the work done.
The court is not satisfied with the quality of your work.
“We didn’t give you a 110-page order for you to be silent about it,” Kumar said.
If at least one more brick is laid, we will order to remove all existing buildings.
Kumar heads the National Green Tribunal (NZT), a judicial body established in 2010 to stop the rapid pollution of the environment that has accompanied the turbulent economic growth of recent decades.
During this time, the Tribunal was able to consider more than 10,000 lawsuits related to air pollution, garbage collection, geological development, toxic waste and dam construction.
In two of the three cases, the court decides on the termination of the construction leading to pollution.
The rates are incredibly high: In less than 60 years since India’s declaration of independence for industrial development, India has turned from a country of virgin jungles to one of the most overpopulated and polluted countries in the world.
Particularly acute problem is in large cities, where the development of infrastructure does not hasten for rapid urbanization: cities are covered with dense smog, rivers are filled with pesticides and wastes of enterprises and households, and few of the newly built houses are built.
Despite the formal support of the green movement by the state, NZT is regularly criticized by the government of Narendra Modi, as it often becomes the main reason for the cancellation of major investment projects.
In May this year, the environment minister called the court’s decisions “extreme” and “unfulfilled.”
Sometimes the court’s decision is really impossible to comply with the deadline set by the court, confirms environmental lawyer Raj Panjwani.
However, non-executable Dadlines also have a positive side: at least they make responsible people move.
“His main goal is to override this system,” adds the lawyer.
The Green Tribunal has already repeatedly cancelled large structures: at its expense, the construction of the airport, power plants and hundreds of smaller structures was terminated.
At the same time, people also try not to forget: for example, during the discussion of the fate of the pharmaceutical company in the state of Telagna, which contaminated the local river with fluoride.
We can close your factory, but we are also responsible for the economic consequences.
“People will lose their jobs,” Kumar said in a statement.
However, such explanations are far from always understood by ordinary people, whose lives can change thanks to a single brush of a pen.
In April, the Tribunal decided to ban all vehicles older than 10 years from entering the capital, which caused public outrage.
Despite a sharp decline in popularity and a squabble of criticism, Swatanter Kumar refused to cancel the decision.
Instead, he asked the Delhi government for statistics on inbound and outbound road transport, as well as offered to buy 10,000 additional buses, knowing in advance at the factories whether they were able to fulfill such an order.
As the court’s attention began to be drawn to sources of pollution such as landfills, fuel quality, and even road accidents, popular anger began to subside a bit.
But the most painful theme of the principled judge was the Ganges River Cleanup Program, with the pump announced by Prime Minister Narendra Modi last year.
When it comes to the Ganges, sacred to the river Indians, the judge often stops holding back his emotions and turns to screaming.
Do you know what the word "holy" means?
Someone poured water from the Ganges into the statue of God, and there were fecal matter in it, the judge says.
You continue to pollute the river because you think: Gang is Gang, he will take away all our sins.
This is a river that we worship and see what you do with it every day.
The Gang cleanup is the most ambitious and expensive environmental project announced by the new government.
Currently, the number of fecal bacteria in this river exceeds the norm by more than 120 times.
Every year from 1.5 to 3 of the 700 million indus swimming in it die from infectious diseases.
In February, Narendra Modi even donated money to the Ganges Rescue Fund to sell his costume, in which he met Barack Obama and 455 other items from his personal collection.
Ecologists immediately accused the prime minister of populism: the suit was bought for $700,000, while cleaning the river requires at least eight billion.
Supporters of the Green Tribunal agree that India will have to go a long way before it can call itself a developed country, but do not believe that the price of progress should be ecology.
“In a developing country, talking about the environment is often seen as an unacceptable luxury,” said Malika Bhanot, an activist with the Gang’s Call.
And the court is trying to find a golden middle between ecology and development.”
