Xi Jinping calls for making the economy more open to the world
The economy must become more open to the whole world to boost its growth, President Xi Jinping said on Tuesday in a speech to a group tasked with leading reforms.
“China should focus on attracting foreign investors and experts and developing a policy of openness,” he said, addressing the participants of the 16th meeting of the Central Group’s Committee on Comprehensive Deepening Reforms.
According to him, expanding openness and deepening reforms will give the economy a new impetus and vitality and provide a new space for economic development.
The lead group adopted a number of directives, including the introduction of regulation of investor access to the market, change of border control rules, promotion of state-owned enterprises (SOEs), attracting private capital, and revision of the resident registration system.
According to the statement, a list of sectors of economy and production that are not available for investment will be drawn up.
The system will be phased out through trial programs.
This is an important step as it will give the market a more significant role in the distribution of resources, ensuring business legitimacy and increasing openness, as stated in the statement.
The government will also weaken control over the powers it provides to companies, thereby ensuring that companies themselves will run their business.
The statement also said that China would allow border regions to master new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms for strengthening local growth.
Even more areas will be available to private investors in order to increase the openness of the state-controlled sectors of the economy.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investors and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies, as well as provide them with better conditions," the statement said.
In addition, the procedure for submitting applications for a permanent residence permit for foreigners, or "green card", will be facilitated by optimizing the requirements and simplifying the application process itself.
The meeting also discussed the protection of the rights of lawyers and the training of professional judges and prosecutors.
According to the official report released after the meeting, it was also attended by Prime Minister Li Ketzen and Ministers Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli.
